      <bioghist encodinganalog="MARC 545">
         <head id="a2" altrender="biography">BIOGRAPHICAL NOTE </head>
         <p>Schaap was born in New York City on September 27, 1934. He earned a B.S. from Cornell
            University in 1955 and an M.S. in journalism from Columbia University in 1956. He was
            sports editor, then general editor, then senior editor for <title>Newsweek</title> from
            1956-1963, and in 1964 became city editor of the <title>New York Herald Tribune</title>.
            He wrote articles for <title>Sports Illustrated</title>, the <title>Saturday Evening
               Post</title>, and other magazines. His books include <title>Mickey Mantle -
               Indispensable Yankee</title>; <title>Paul Hornung - Pro Football's Golden
            Boy</title>; <title>An Illustrated History of the Olympics</title>; <title>Instant
               Replay</title> (about Jerry Kramer); <title>RFK</title>; and <title>Turned
            On</title>. He also edited autobiographies of Joe Namath, Frank Beard, and Tom
            Seaver.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="MARC 520">
         <head id="a3">COLLECTION DESCRIPTION</head>
         <p>Includes research notes, newspaper clippings, tape recordings and typed transcriptions,
            drafts of articles and books, and related material from Schaap's career as an author and
            editor. Also includes material regarding drug addiction, and research material
            concerning Robert F. Kennedy.</p>
      </scopecontent>
